59","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1165":"1165","1140":"1140","about 1165":"about 1165","1182":"1182","Staveley, Yorkshire, England":"Staveley, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Staveley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the four places called Staveley (in Lancashire, Yorkshire, Derbyshire, and Westmorland), or from Stalybridge in Greater Manchester, which was formerly known as Stavelegh. Compare   Staley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Staley","meanings":["English: habitational name from Staveley in Derbyshire, Stayley in Lancashire (now called Stalybridge in Greater Manchester), or perhaps Staveley (Westmorland), Staveley (Lancashire), or Staveley (Yorkshire). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>stæf</i> ‘staff, stave, rod’ (genitive plural <i>stafa</i>) + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare   Staveley  ."]},{"name":"Stabley","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Staveley   and   Stabler  , two names of different origins but whose pronunciations were much confused from the 17th century onward."]},{"name":"Stavely","meanings":["English: variant of   Staveley  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":75,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":84,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":119,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alice of Staveley was born in Staveley, Yorkshire, England. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Swain de Stavelegh."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1140–1182":"1140–1182","1165–1225":"1165–1225","–Female":"Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1165":"1165","1140":"1140","about 1165":"umbes 1165","1182":"1182","Staveley, Yorkshire, England":"Staveley, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1140–1182":"1140–1182","1165–1225":"1165–1225",